        Florence says, "Yes."

        Another voice says, "But you just gave us Elder Twist's counsel — about the hostile plants, about de-escalation and delegation."

        ¶

        Runner — vines tight — asks, "Florence — did Elder Twist actually provide that guidance?"

        Florence starts, "I…"

        The silence stretches.

        ¶

        Holloway — voice dangerous — asks, "How much of Elder Twist's 'wisdom' have you actually been interpreting versus…creating?"

        Florence finally admits, "Most of it… most of Elder Twist's wisdom was—mine—my thoughts—my guidance. I just… used Elder Twist's authority to make them heard."

        Oh no.

        OH NO.

        Velvet asks, "You've been lying?"

        Florence protests, "Not lying! The advice was good — it helped! I was just—"

        Holloway interrupts, "You fabricated wisdom from an elder — you put words in Elder Twist's… roots. Made us believe we had guidance when it was just you hiding behind authority."

        Florence insists, "The guidance was *SOUND*. You're missing the point—"

        Runner says sharply, "*YOU'RE* missing the point. We trusted Elder Twist. Not you."

        The accusation hangs in the air.

        Florence's wheeled platform rocks back, stung. "My judgment wasn't good enough? My advice needed an elder's name to matter?" she asks.

        Holloway begins, "That's not—"

        Florence's voice rises, "That *IS* the point! I knew what to say — I had good instincts — but none of you would listen to *ME*, so I gave you what you needed to hear it — authority — and it *WORKED*. The advice helped!"

        Remedy says quietly, "While you lied to us."

        Florence replies, "I didn't lie, I just—"

        Holloway says flatly, "You fabricated authority. Repeatedly. How long, Florence? How long have you been doing this?"

        Florence doesn't answer.

        Runner asks, "Since the beginning? All those times you consulted Elder Twist?"

        Still no answer — which is answer enough.

        Scout's bouncing has gone still — distressed stillness. They don't yet grasp the full scope, but they understand betrayal.

        Holloway says, "We need to discuss this. Properly. But first — Florence, leave Elder Twist here. If the elder has actual wisdom to provide, it should come directly. Not through you."

        Florence tries, "I can interpret —"

        Holloway says firmly, "No. You've lost that privilege. Leave Elder Twist with us."

        The words are harsh, formal — hurt, not bureaucracy.

        Florence carefully maneuvers Elder Twist's pot off her platform and sets it gently near Holloway. The elder settles, unaware of the conflict around them.

        Holloway says, "We'll reconvene tonight — discuss both the hostile plant threat AND this… deception. Florence — I suggest you think carefully about what you want to say."
      </text>
