        Florence doesn't respond — she wheels away slowly, alone for the first time since I've known her. She always carried Elder Twist; that was her role, her identity. Now she's just Florence — no borrowed authority. And from the slump of her platform, she's realizing what that means.

        After she's gone, we all stand in uncomfortable silence.
        ¶
        I finally say, "The advice about de-escalation… was it actually good advice?"

        Holloway — tired — says, "That's not the point, Kira."

        I say, "I know it's not *the* point — but is it *a* point? Was the guidance Florence gave, whatever the source — was it sound?"

        Holloway — frustrated — says, "Yes, probably — Florence has good tactical instincts — but—"

        Remedy says, "But she lied — and we can't trust lies, even if they're useful."

        I ask, "Can't we? Or can't you?"

        They all look at me.

        I struggle to articulate this. "I mean… she gave good advice that helped. The source was false, but the content was valuable. For me, that matters."

        Holloway — careful — says, "For us — the dishonesty matters. Authority frameworks require trust. She violated that."

        I point out, "But you just learned authority frameworks don't work — Elder Heartwood failed, the HR manuals failed — now you're saying Florence failed because she violated authority principles?"

        Holloway doesn't answer.

        Runner — firm — says, "Tonight — we discuss this tonight. Right now, we still have hostile plants marking territory. Whatever Florence did, that threat is real."

        Right. The actual crisis still exists; we've just added an internal crisis on top of it.

        Scout presses against my leg — comfort, solidarity, confusion. They don't understand all the complexity, but they understand something's broken.

        Holloway says, "Tonight — we'll figure out both problems. Somehow."

        But as we disperse to handle immediate needs, I can feel the fracture — the trust we just built, learning to rely on ourselves instead of external authority, is damaged now. Internal betrayal hits exactly when we need cohesion.

        The hostile plants are organized and threatening — and we just became significantly weaker.
      </text>
